To solve this problem, we need to use concepts from both optics (lenses) and algebraic manipulation.


#### Part (a): Position of the Final Image

First Lens:
The formula for thin lenses relates the distance \( u_1 \), which represents how far away the object is before it hits the lens (\(-u\)), its focal length \( f_1 = -10\) cm, and where light will converge after passing through the lens:

$$ 
\dfrac{1}{f}=\dfrac {1}{v}-\dfrac {1}{-u}
$$

For our setup,
\[ v_{L1}=? ,~ u=-40 ~cm,\quad f=+10 ~cm.\]

Substituting these values into the equation gives us,

$$ 
\dfrac{1}{10}=\dfrac {1}{v_{L1}}-\left(\dfrac {-1}{40}\right)
\\[5pt]
\dfrac{-1}{10}+\dfrac{1}{40}&=&\dfrac{1}{v_{L1}}
\\\dfrac{\cancelto{8}{-(4)}}{{\color{red}{4\times }}10} + {\color{blue}{\dfrac{(1)}{4}}} &=& \dfrac{1}{v_{L1}}
\\[-6mm]&& \\ && \\
\dfrac{-7}{40} & =&   \dfrac{1}{v_{L1}}
\\[9pt]\therefore~~ v_{L1}&=& -\dfrac{40}{7}\\[10pt]&\approx& -5.71 ~~cm
$$


